[{"thread":{"id":"1356635933637873885","type":11,"last_message_id":"1356659769892409534","flags":0,"guild_id":"1212332642801025064","name":"Infrahub - Air Gapped (Offline Environment) Install Procedure","parent_id":"1301914405176475729","rate_limit_per_user":0,"bitrate":64000,"user_limit":0,"rtc_region":null,"owner_id":"1352654639522123826","thread_metadata":{"archived":true,"archive_timestamp":"2025-05-01T16:08:35.954000+00:00","auto_archive_duration":4320,"locked":false,"create_timestamp":"2025-04-01T14:26:51.656000+00:00"},"message_count":5,"member_count":3,"total_message_sent":5,"applied_tags":["1301915235380363266"]},"messages":[{"type":0,"content":"Thank you guys. Just tested this out and it worked perfectly. Much appreciated.","mentions":[],"mention_roles":[],"attachments":[],"embeds":[],"timestamp":"2025-04-01T16:01:34.662000+00:00","edited_timestamp":null,"flags":0,"components":[],"id":"1356659769892409534","channel_id":"1356635933637873885","author":{"id":"1352654639522123826","username":"thomas_72011","avatar":null,"discriminator":"0","public_flags":0,"flags":0,"banner":null,"accent_color":null,"global_name":"Thomas","avatar_decoration_data":null,"collectibles":null,"display_name_styles":null,"banner_color":null,"clan":null,"primary_guild":null},"pinned":false,"mention_everyone":false,"tts":false,"position":4,"reactions":[{"emoji":{"id":null,"name":"ðŸ‘"},"count":2,"count_details":{"burst":0,"normal":2},"burst_colors":[],"me_burst":false,"burst_me":false,"me":false,"burst_count":0},{"emoji":{"id":null,"name":"ðŸŽ‰"},"count":1,"count_details":{"burst":0,"normal":1},"burst_colors":[],"me_burst":false,"burst_me":false,"me":false,"burst_count":0}]},{"type":0,"content":"Hello,\nThat should be enough, you also need to grab the docker compose file itself using\n`curl https://infrahub.opsmill.io/enterprise > docker-compose.yml`\n\nThen assuming you have docker compose installed on the offline system, you can just `docker compose -p -f docker-compose.yml up -d`","mentions":[],"mention_roles":[],"attachments":[],"embeds":[],"timestamp":"2025-04-01T15:43:20.081000+00:00","edited_timestamp":null,"flags":0,"components":[],"id":"1356655178887069827","channel_id":"1356635933637873885","author":{"id":"1220422159676084304","username":"fatih_10382_62805","avatar":null,"discriminator":"0","public_flags":0,"flags":0,"banner":null,"accent_color":null,"global_name":"fatih","avatar_decoration_data":null,"collectibles":null,"display_name_styles":null,"banner_color":null,"clan":{"identity_guild_id":"1212332642801025064","identity_enabled":true,"tag":"OTTO","badge":"40122d86938d2a7824dfd9bd695abe81"},"primary_guild":{"identity_guild_id":"1212332642801025064","identity_enabled":true,"tag":"OTTO","badge":"40122d86938d2a7824dfd9bd695abe81"}},"pinned":false,"mention_everyone":false,"tts":false,"position":3},{"type":0,"content":"On the online system, is the best way to this command (from the install guide):\ncurl https://infrahub.opsmill.io/enterprise | sudo docker compose -p infrahub -f - up -d\n\nAnd then use \"docker save\", which will produce a tar file. Is there anything else required on the offline system other than \"docker image import\"?","mentions":[],"mention_roles":[],"attachments":[],"embeds":[],"timestamp":"2025-04-01T15:12:14.073000+00:00","edited_timestamp":null,"flags":0,"components":[],"id":"1356647352282255400","channel_id":"1356635933637873885","author":{"id":"1352654639522123826","username":"thomas_72011","avatar":null,"discriminator":"0","public_flags":0,"flags":0,"banner":null,"accent_color":null,"global_name":"Thomas","avatar_decoration_data":null,"collectibles":null,"display_name_styles":null,"banner_color":null,"clan":null,"primary_guild":null},"pinned":false,"mention_everyone":false,"tts":false,"position":2},{"type":0,"content":"So the \"docker image import\" method - would that still require running docker compose on the offline system to get the containers up and running?","mentions":[],"mention_roles":[],"attachments":[],"embeds":[],"timestamp":"2025-04-01T15:09:40.283000+00:00","edited_timestamp":null,"flags":0,"components":[],"id":"1356646707240239125","channel_id":"1356635933637873885","author":{"id":"1352654639522123826","username":"thomas_72011","avatar":null,"discriminator":"0","public_flags":0,"flags":0,"banner":null,"accent_color":null,"global_name":"Thomas","avatar_decoration_data":null,"collectibles":null,"display_name_styles":null,"banner_color":null,"clan":null,"primary_guild":null},"pinned":false,"mention_everyone":false,"tts":false,"position":1},{"type":0,"content":"There are a few methods. Images can be downloaded and transfered to the host and imported using `docker image import`. \n\nAnother option would be if you have a private container repository the images could be imported into and then you could point docker or kube to pull images from an internal repo.","mentions":[],"mention_roles":[],"attachments":[],"embeds":[],"timestamp":"2025-04-01T14:46:59.565000+00:00","edited_timestamp":null,"flags":0,"components":[],"id":"1356640999975288832","channel_id":"1356635933637873885","author":{"id":"227091130561331200","username":"minitriga.","avatar":"71ac6f8da9c358794381d5d430c53316","discriminator":"0","public_flags":0,"flags":0,"banner":null,"accent_color":null,"global_name":"Alex Gittings","avatar_decoration_data":null,"collectibles":null,"display_name_styles":null,"banner_color":null,"clan":null,"primary_guild":null},"pinned":false,"mention_everyone":false,"tts":false},{"type":0,"content":"Hello all -\n\nI am pretty new with Docker and stuff like that. I was wondering if it's possible to install Infrahub in an offline environment (e.g. a network that isn't connected to the Internet).\n\nThe main ways to get Infrahub up and running, from what I've seen, are basically Docker compose, and Kubernetes.\n\nThe Docker compose \"route\" requires the server to call out and fetch images / install info from the Internet. Our environment doesn't allow that unfortunately.\n\nEven a method maybe where you have an online Ubuntu server connected to the Internet, and have that run the docker compose stuff, and then somehow save a snapshot of that image and transfer it to the offline system and get it up and running on there.\n\nCan anybody think of a way to get this to work? I'd really like to test out Infrahub, but can't seem to get around this.","mentions":[],"mention_roles":[],"attachments":[],"embeds":[],"timestamp":"2025-04-01T14:26:51.656000+00:00","edited_timestamp":"2025-04-01T14:41:34.456000+00:00","flags":0,"components":[],"id":"1356635933637873885","channel_id":"1356635933637873885","author":{"id":"1352654639522123826","username":"thomas_72011","avatar":null,"discriminator":"0","public_flags":0,"flags":0,"banner":null,"accent_color":null,"global_name":"Thomas","avatar_decoration_data":null,"collectibles":null,"display_name_styles":null,"banner_color":null,"clan":null,"primary_guild":null},"pinned":false,"mention_everyone":false,"tts":false}]}]